I"G<h1 id="data-downloads">Data downloads</h1>
<p>GitHub.com allows you to upload data files to your repositories. While the platform works best with text-based files, you can still upload .zipped Shapefiles or images and store them too. Just be aware that <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/free-pro-team@latest/github/managing-large-files/what-is-my-disk-quota#file-and-repository-size-limitations">GitHub recommends keeping your repos less than 1GB</a> in total file size.</p>

<p>Since our beloved .geojson is text-based, it renders really well in the GitHub UI – <a href="https://github.com/UBCGeodata/ubc-geospatial-opendata/blob/master/ubcv/locations/geojson/ubcv_buildings.geojson">like this geojson of UBC’s buildings</a>. However, if you want someone to download the file in your workshop, you’ll need to provide a link.</p>

<p class="note">Best practice is to transfer your data files as one (or a minimal) zipped package of content. This way you can preserve a directory structure and avoid losing any auxiliary files. The downside is that GitHub won’t render them in the browser (╯°□°)╯︵ ┻━┻</p>

<h2 id="linking-your-data-for-download">Linking your data for download</h2>

<p>To be able to link your data, you’ll just need the path from the page you’re providing the link to the file itself.</p>

<p>This</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>[Download Data](../data/us-national-parks.geojson)
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Will provide a link like this:</p>

<p><a href="../data/us-national-parks.geojson">Download Data</a></p>

<h2 id="adding-a-button">Adding a button</h2>
<p>Maybe you want that link to look more apparent?? Well, why not try a button!</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>[Download Data](../data/us-national-parks.geojson){: .btn .btn-blue }
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Looks like:</p>

<p><a href="../data/us-national-parks.geojson" class="btn btn-blue">Download Data</a></p>

